The pre-initiative docs snapshot is empty, so I'll reason from the stated stack (Next.js 16, Payload CMS 3, Tailwind CSS 4, Elan design system) and the precise symptoms you described. Let me give you a thorough, file-specific fix.

---

## Diagnosis

Two distinct, compounding problems:

1. **Bold-abuse:** The source markdown used `**…**` as inline scan anchors — short label fragments like `**Per user.**`, `**Scaffolding.**`, `**Key insight:**`. Payload stores these as `<strong>` nodes in its Lexical rich-text JSON. The prose renderer faithfully re-emits them. Result: 36 `<strong>` spans scattered across 7 body blocks, visually fragmenting every paragraph into a ransom-note of weight changes.

2. **Visual hierarchy collapse:** Each body block is rendered as a flat wall of text. The scan-anchor bolds were *masquerading as* section sub-headers in the original markdown — once they're in flowing prose they produce fake weight emphasis rather than structural separation. Simultaneously, the space between adjacent `<section>` or `<article>` blocks is either missing or uses the same `gap` as inter-paragraph spacing, so section breaks and paragraph breaks feel identical in weight.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Markdown-origin scan anchors leaked into display prose.**
The source document was written as a working draft, not as a publication. `**bold**` fragments were used as the *author's own* in-document navigation aids. No sanitisation or editorial transform was applied at ingest time or render time to strip them before display.

**EAP-027 — Section rhythm delegated entirely to the prose plugin with no explicit inter-section spacing token.**
The Tailwind `prose` plugin (or the Elan `ElanProse` wrapper) controls intra-body typography but the *between-body* gap is left to whatever default block margin the parent flex/grid container provides, which collapses to the same visual weight as an `<h3>` gap.

---

## Fix

### 1. Strip scan-anchor `<strong>` nodes from Payload Lexical output

These are `<strong>` nodes whose *entire text content* is a short label ending in `.` or `:` (or both) — the pattern `**Foo.**` / `**Key insight:**`. Real semantic bolds (a proper noun, a technical term mid-sentence) are multi-word fragments *inside* a longer sentence.

**`src/components/essay/RichTextRenderer.tsx`** (or wherever Payload's Lexical nodes are walked):

```tsx
// ─── src/components/essay/RichTextRenderer.tsx ────────────────────────────

/**
 * Serialiser for a Lexical TextNode with the FORMAT_BOLD flag set.
 *
 * Rule: a <strong> is a *scan anchor* — not semantic emphasis — when
 * its full trimmed text matches the pattern:
 *   • ends with "." or ":" (label punctuation)
 *   • AND is ≤ 5 words
 *
 * Those nodes are demoted to plain <span> (no weight change).
 * Everything else keeps <strong>.
 */

const SCAN_ANCHOR_RE = /^[\w ,''()\-]{1,40}[.:]$/;

function isScanAnchor(text: string): boolean {
  const t = text.trim();
  return SCAN_ANCHOR_RE.test(t) && t.split(/\s+/).length <= 5;
}

// Inside your node serialiser switch / if-chain:
case 'text': {
  const isBold = (node.format & IS_BOLD) !== 0;

  if (isBold && isScanAnchor(node.text)) {
    // Demote: strip the weight, preserve the text.
    // The node still renders — it just loses its bold.
    return (
      <span key={key} className="text-inherit">
        {node.text}
      </span>
    );
  }

  if (isBold) {
    return <strong key={key}>{node.text}</strong>;
  }

  return <span key={key}>{node.text}</span>;
}
```

> **Why not strip entirely?** The text itself is still meaningful; only the *weight signal* is noise. Removing the characters would silently alter the author's prose.

---

### 2. Add an editorial-transform pass at Payload ingest

The renderer fix is the *display* safety net. Pair it with a one-time migration that cleans the stored Lexical JSON so you're not masking a data smell forever.

**`src/migrations/stripScanAnchorBolds.ts`**

```ts
// ─── src/migrations/stripScanAnchorBolds.ts ───────────────────────────────
import type { MigrateUpArgs } from '@payloadcms/db-postgres'

const SCAN_ANCHOR_RE = /^[\w ,''()\-]{1,40}[.:]$/

function stripBoldFromScanAnchors(nodes: any[]): any[] {
  return nodes.map((node) => {
    if (node.type === 'text' && node.format & 1 /* IS_BOLD */) {
      const t = (node.text as string).trim()
      if (SCAN_ANCHOR_RE.test(t) && t.split(/\s+/).length <= 5) {
        return { ...node, format: node.format & ~1 } // clear bold bit
      }
    }
    if (Array.isArray(node.children)) {
      return { ...node, children: stripBoldFromScanAnchors(node.children) }
    }
    return node
  })
}

export async function up({ payload }: MigrateUpArgs): Promise<void> {
  const essays = await payload.find({
    collection: 'essays',   // ← your collection slug
    limit: 100,
    depth: 0,
  })

  for (const essay of essays.docs) {
    const cleaned = stripBoldFromScanAnchors(essay.content?.root?.children ?? [])
    await payload.update({
      collection: 'essays',
      id: essay.id,
      data: {
        content: {
          ...essay.content,
          root: { ...essay.content.root, children: cleaned },
        },
      },
    })
  }
}
```

Run with: `pnpm payload migrate`

---

### 3. Fix inter-section visual hierarchy

**`src/components/essay/EssayLayout.tsx`** (the component that maps body blocks to sections):

```tsx
// ─── src/components/essay/EssayLayout.tsx ────────────────────────────────
//
// BEFORE (collapsed hierarchy):
//
// <div className="flex flex-col gap-8">
//   {bodies.map((body) => (
//     <ElanProse key={body.id} content={body.richText} />
//   ))}
// </div>
//
// AFTER:

export function EssayLayout({ bodies }: { bodies: EssayBody[] }) {
  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col">
      {bodies.map((body, i) => (
        <section
          key={body.id}
          // ┌─ inter-section breathing room: 3rem top (except first)
          // │  This is the "section break" signal — heavier than the
          // │  prose-plugin's inter-paragraph gap (1.5em / ~1.5rem).
          className={cn(
            'relative',
            i !== 0 && 'mt-12',          // 3rem — section break
          )}
          aria-label={body.heading ?? undefined}
        >
          {/* ── Optional section rule — a hairline above each section
                provides a *spatial* separator that doesn't rely on
                size or weight contrast alone.                        */}
          {i !== 0 && (
            <hr className="
              mb-10
              border-t border-border/30   /* Elan border token, 30 % opacity */
            " />
          )}

          {/* ── If the body block has a heading field in Payload,
                render it here as an h2 so the hierarchy is explicit
                in the DOM, not implied by a bold sentence fragment. */}
          {body.heading && (
            <h2 className="
              font-display text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight
              text-foreground mb-4
            ">
              {body.heading}
            </h2>
          )}

          <ElanProse content={body.richText} />
        </section>
      ))}
    </div>
  )
}
```

---

### 4. Tighten the `ElanProse` bold style so remaining legitimate bolds are visually intentional, not accidental

**`src/components/ui/ElanProse.tsx`** (or wherever the Tailwind `prose` overrides live):

```tsx
// ─── src/components/ui/ElanProse.tsx ─────────────────────────────────────
//
// Tailwind CSS 4 uses @utility / @layer for prose overrides.
// Keep bold text at font-semibold (600), NOT font-bold (700).
// 700 weight reads as "heading" in long-form text; 600 reads as
// "important term" — semantically correct for inline emphasis.

export function ElanProse({
  content,
  className,
}: {
  content: SerializedEditorState
  className?: string
}) {
  return (
    <div
      className={cn(
        // Base prose scale
        'prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert',
        'prose-base leading-relaxed',

        // ── Bold override: semibold, not bold ──────────────────────
        // Prevents legitimate <strong> from reading as a heading.
        '[&_strong]:font-semibold [&_strong]:text-foreground',

        // ── Paragraph spacing ─────────────────────────────────────
        // prose default is 1.25em; bump to 1.5em for long-form
        '[&_p]:my-[1.5em]',

        className,
      )}
    >
      <LexicalRenderer state={content} />
    </div>
  )
}
```

---

## Summary of all changes

| File | What changes | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `src/components/essay/RichTextRenderer.tsx` | `isScanAnchor()` guard demotes `<strong>` → `<span>` at render time | Immediate display fix, zero data risk |
| `src/migrations/stripScanAnchorBolds.ts` | One-time Payload migration clears bold bit from scan-anchor nodes in stored Lexical JSON | Fixes the data source, not just the mask |
| `src/components/essay/EssayLayout.tsx` | `mt-12` inter-section gap + `<hr>` hairline separator + explicit `<h2>` from `body.heading` | Separates section-break weight from paragraph-break weight |
| `src/components/ui/ElanProse.tsx` | `[&_strong]:font-semibold` override | Keeps remaining legitimate bolds from reading as headings |

---

## Principle

**Never let authoring conventions leak into display conventions.** A `**bold**` in a working draft markdown file is the *author talking to themselves*. The moment that document becomes a rendered publication, those annotations must be transformed or stripped at the boundary — ingest or serialisation — not tolerated as a visual property of the final artifact. The structural hierarchy of a multi-section essay must come from explicit DOM elements (`<section>`, `<h2>`, `<hr>`) carrying explicit spacing tokens, not from weight accidents in inline text nodes (EAP-027).
